<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="generalized-eigenspaces">
  <title>Generalized Eigenspaces</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Suppose that <m>T:V\to V</m> is an operator with minimal polynomial 
      <m>p(x)=(x-\lambda)^k q(x)</m> with <m>q(\lambda)\neq 0</m>. Then <m>\lambda</m> is
      an eigenvalue and
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>G_\lambda = \nul((T-\lambda I)^k)</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      is called the generalized eigenspace. An element <m>\vvec</m> in
      <m>G_\lambda</m> is called a generalized eigenvector.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\vvec</m> is a generalized eigenvector with eigenvalue
        <m>\lambda</m>. Explain why <m>(T-\lambda I)^k\vvec = 0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        What can you conclude about the annihilating polynomial <m>p_\vvec</m>?
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\lambda</m> and <m>\mu</m> are two distinct eigenvalues.
        Use these observations to explain why <m>G_\lambda \cap G_\mu = \{0\}</m>.
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>\dim V = 5</m> and <m>V_1</m> and <m>V_2</m> are subspaces
        of <m>V</m> with <m>\dim V_1 = 3</m> and <m>\dim V_2 = 2</m>. Then there
        are bases <m>\{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3\}</m> for <m>V_1</m> and
        <m>\{\vvec_4,\vvec_5\}</m> for <m>V_2</m>. Explain why the set
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>\{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3,\vvec_4,\vvec_5\}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        is linearly dependent.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use this fact to show that <m>V_1 \cap V_2 \neq \{0\}</m>.
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        Suppose that <m>p(x)=(x-2)^3(x-4)^2</m>. If <m>\wvec</m> is in
        <m>\range((T-4I)^2)</m>, explain why <m>(T-2I)^3(\wvec)=0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain why
        <m>\range((T-4I)^2) \subset \nul((T-2I)^3)=G_2</m> and hence
        <m>\dim \range((T-4I)^2) \leq \dim G_2</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain why
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>\dim G_4 + \dim \range((T-4I)^2) = \dim V.</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain why
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>\dim G_4 + \dim G_2 \geq \dim V.</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Since <m>G_4 \cap G_2 = \{0\}</m>, explain why
        <m>\dim G_4 + \dim G_2 = \dim V</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain why <m>G_4 \oplus G_2 = V</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain why both <m>G_4</m> and <m>G_2</m> are <m>T</m>-invariant.
      </p>
      <p>
        If <m>\bcal</m> is a basis for <m>G_4</m> and <m>\ccal</m> is a basis
        for <m>G_2</m>, then <m>\dcal=\bcal\cup\ccal</m> is a basis for <m>V</m>.
        Explain why
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>
        \coords{T}{\dcal,\dcal} =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          \coords{T}{\bcal,\bcal} \amp \zerovec \\
          \zerovec \amp \coords{T}{\ccal,\ccal}
        \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>
        What you have found here is generally true: If the minimal polynomial
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>
        p(x) = (x-\lambda_1)^{k_1}(x-\lambda_2)^{k_2}\cdots(x-\lambda_m)^{k_m},
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        then
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>
        V = G_{\lambda_1} \oplus G_{\lambda_2} \oplus \cdots \oplus G_{\lambda_m}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        and there is a basis for <m>V</m> such that the matrix representing
        <m>T</m> is block diagonal, where the diagonal blocks are the
        representations of <m>T|_{G_{\lambda_j}}</m>.
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      This worksheet develops the structure of generalized eigenspaces and shows
      how they decompose a vector space into invariant subspaces corresponding
      to the factors of the minimal polynomial.
    </p>
  </conclusion>

</worksheet>
